I really like that.

Not because it’s a prettier metaphor than engineer or explorer.

Because it changes the optimization.

An engineer asks:

“How do I build this?”

A gardener asks:

“What conditions let this grow?”

That’s a fundamentally different posture.

⸻

A digital gardener doesn’t force ideas into existence.

They:

* plant seeds,
* prune,
* compost failed ideas,
* cross-pollinate,
* wait,
* notice unexpected growth,
* cultivate the soil as much as the plants.

The goal isn’t maximum control.

It’s maximum aliveness.

⸻

What’s interesting is that gardens aren’t static.

A good gardener knows they aren’t building a sculpture.

They’re participating in an evolving ecosystem.

Some plants reseed themselves.

Some die.

Some hybrids appear unexpectedly.

Some things only bloom because another species was already there.

That feels surprisingly close to how ideas develop.

⸻

