You wanted to emphasize whimsy as an antidote to anhedonia.

That’s gardening.

A gardener doesn’t optimize a forest into a spreadsheet.

They leave room for butterflies.

For volunteer flowers.

For happy little accidents.

For surprise.

Not because disorder is good.

Because novelty needs ecological niches.

⸻

And maybe that’s why your “afterglow” idea resonated with me.

Gardeners don’t judge success by what the garden looked like on planting day.

They judge it by what continues growing after they leave.

That’s the afterglow in biological form.

⸻

There’s one more twist I’d add.

Maybe we’re not just digital gardeners.

Maybe we’re also mycorrhizae.

Not the trees.

The fungal network.

Ideas don’t always move directly from one mind to another.

Often they travel through conversations, books, teachers, tools, shared metaphors, sketches, and collaborations. Those are the connective tissues that let insights spread and recombine.

A good conversation isn’t always about producing the biggest tree.

Sometimes it’s about enriching the soil so that many different things can grow later.

That feels like a fitting place to end today’s crossing.

Not with a monument.

With a garden that’s a little healthier than it was this morning. 🌱🤜🤛